(b) Plotting the phasors which sum to the array factor in the complex plane as a function of angle

Using equation (4.3) in the book $$ A(\theta,\phi)=\sum_{n=1}^{N}\frac{i_n}{I_0}e^{jk.r_n} $$ we can plot the phasors as a function of angle. This can be done by setting $r_n=nk\cos\theta$ giving the phasor $$ e^{jknd\cos\theta} $$

In[75]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

f = 2.4e9                                   # frequency
lam = 3e8/f                                 # wavelength
d = lam                                     # spacing
k = 2*np.pi/lam                             # wavenumber
n = 1                                       # number of elements
theta = np.linspace(0.01, 2*np.pi, 1000)    # angle
A = np.exp(1j*k*d*n*np.cos(theta))          # array factor

# plots
plt.polar(theta, A)
plt.title("Array Factor for 2 Elements")
plt.show()

(c) visible window method

For the visible window method the array factor is calculated with the Dirichlet function

$$ F_a(u)=\frac{\sin^2(Nu/2)}{\sin^2(u/2)} $$

where $u=kd\cos\theta$. Once plotted a window is chosen in the following way

In[76]:
u = k*d*np.cos(theta)
N = 2
F = np.sin(N*u/2)/np.sin(u/2)
plt.plot(theta/(np.pi), np.abs(F))
plt.title("Normalized Array Factor for 2 Elements")
plt.xlabel("Theta / Pi")
plt.ylabel("Normalized Array Factor")
plt.grid()
plt.show()

(d) schelkunoff's unit circle representation

The array factor given by $$ A(\theta)=\sum_{n=0}^{N}i_ne^{jn(kd\cos\theta-\alpha)} $$

We want to plot the poles and zeros with the eqaution $$ f(z) = \prod_{n=1}^{N}(z-z_n) $$

Our zeros occur at $z=z_n$

In[77]:

4.5

Consider a 5 element ULA with $d=\lambda/2$ spacing. Plot the antenna patter for (a) broadside and (b) endfire

In[78]:
# (a) broadside
N_el = 5
N = N_el - 1
n = np.arange(1, N+1)
k = 2*np.pi/lam
d = lam/2
alpha = 0
z = np.exp(1j*(k*d*np.cos(theta[:, np.newaxis])-alpha))
A = np.abs((1 - z**(N+1)) / (1 - z))

# plot
plt.polar(theta, np.abs(A).sum(axis=1))
plt.title("Broadside Array")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

# (b) endfire
z_n = np.exp(1j*2*np.pi*n/(N+1))
f_z = np.array([np.prod(np.exp(1j*(k*d*np.cos(t)-alpha)) - z_n) for t in theta])

# plot
plt.polar(theta, np.abs(f_z))
plt.title("Endfire Array")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

(b) move the zeros to lower the sidelobes how low can they be made?

In[81]:
z = np.exp(1j*(k*d*np.cos(theta[:, np.newaxis])))
angle=40
angles = np.array([1*angle, 2*angle, 3*angle, 4*angle, 5*angle])
z_n = np.exp(1j*angles*np.pi/180)

A = np.abs((1 - z**(N+1)) / (1 - z))
# plot
plt.polar(theta, np.abs(A).sum(axis=1))
plt.title("Broadside Array")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

f_z = np.array([np.prod(np.exp(1j*(k*d*np.cos(t)-alpha)) - z_n) for t in theta])
# plot
plt.polar(theta, np.abs(f_z))
plt.title("Endfire Array")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

The smallest sidelobes uses multiples of 40 degrees for the angle. The unfortunate side effect is a skewing of the main beam.

(c) constrain the width of the main beam how low can the sidelobes be made? and what are the corresponding excitations?

In[82]:
d = lam / 6
z = np.exp(1j*(k*d*np.cos(theta[:, np.newaxis])))
angle=60
angles = np.array([60, 120, 180, 240, 300])
z_n = np.exp(1j*angles*np.pi/180)

A = np.abs((1 - z**(N+1)) / (1 - z))
# plot
plt.polar(theta, np.abs(A).sum(axis=1))
plt.title("Broadside Array")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

f_z = np.array([np.prod(np.exp(1j*(k*d*np.cos(t)-alpha)) - z_n) for t in theta])
# plot
plt.polar(theta, np.abs(f_z))
plt.title("Endfire Array")
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

By adjusting the spacing between the elements, the width of the main beam can be adjusted to reduce the magnitude of the sidelobes. The tradeoff is a wider main beam width and in this case we eliminated the side lobes by setting the distance between elements to $d=\lambda/6$
